\section{Title}
Rising temperatures increasing productivity of brown tiger prawn ({\it Penaeus esculentus}) in Moreton Bay (Australia)\\
or\\
Climate effects on the productivity of brown tiger prawn ({\it Penaeus esculentus}) in Moreton Bay (Australia)\\
or\\
Climate change increased productivity of brown tiger prawn ({\it Penaeus esculentus}) in Moreton Bay (Australia)


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\section{Why are we doing this work ? why is this topic important ? Think about the key question you and your audience might have}

\begin{itemize}
\item Environment shapes the dynamic of marine population
\item Understanding effects of climate on fisheries productivity is important to (a) anticipate short-term variations in production and (b) forecast long-terms effects of climate change 
\item Environmental factors are seldom incorporated to stock assessment
\item Regression often fails to identify environmental effects
\item For short-lived species like prawn, the bulk of harvest made each year is composed of new recruits. The productivity of such species depends on factors influencing recruitment. 
\item Tiger prawn recruitment has been shown to be influenced by ....
\item {\bf knowledge of the study area and the species}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Australian waters are low productivity besides estuaries
\item Biological production in estuaries is influenced by climate variability
\item The Brisbane river estuary sustains a brown tiger prawn population located at the southern tip of its distribution
\item Climate change is increasing the proportion of tropical species in subtropical fisheries (Cheung et al, temperature of the catch). 
%\item Temperature was found to play an important on catchability of tiger prawn in Moreton Bay fishery (Kienzle et al.,2014)
\item A SRR has been described for tiger prawn in Moreton Bay because the spawning stock biomass was driven to low level enough to induce a recruitment response (Kienzle et al.,2014, Walters and Martell, 2004)
\item The Ricker SRR relationship was not significant (Kienzle et al.,2014) suggesting that other factors than SSB, possibly environmental factors, were influencing recruitment.
\item Fishery production of short lived species is driven by recruitment. Environmental effects of recruitment can potentially plays a major influence of production of such species %(Studying the dynamic of recruitment is important, in particular for short lived species referred to as recruitment driven stocks)
\item Recruitment is has been shown to vary in response of rainfall (Penn and Caputi, 1986) %thought to vary in response to environmental variations
\end{enumerate}
%\item We propose to use a stock assessment to investigate environmental variable
%\item Understanding environmental drivers of fisheries productivity provides industry with the tools to devise ecologically efficient harvest strategies adapted to future environment [ but beyond industry, it helps understanding the impact of other human activity (dam construction, coastal development, etc...) on natural populations ]
\item {\bf How did you approach the problem}
\begin{enumerate}
%\item We suggest to use stock assessment to investigate the effects of environmental variables on fishery production
%\item Assess which model best describe the variation of catchability ?
%\item How important are daily variations of temperature ?
%\item Is it possible to estimate natural mortality ? and what the implecations of doing so ?
%\item Is recruitment variation an important factor to account for ?
\item We looked at which environmental variable could explain recruitment variability ?
\end{enumerate}

%\item Studying the relationship between stock and recruitment is important especially for short lived species referred to as recruitment driven stocks
%\item About 50\% of the MB tiger prawn SRR remains un-explained
%\item Kienzle et al (2014) showed temperature played an important role in the dynamic of tiger prawn fisheries [Temperature regulate the metabolic process of poikilotherms ]
\item Which environmental variable (rainfall, temperature, ...) explains residual recruitment variability ?
%\item How important is it to include daily measurements of temperature ?
%\item How important is variation of recruitment timing on the dynamic of this fishery ?
%\item Are there evidences of pre-poning of recruitment ? lengthning of the warmer season and fishing season ? Will Moreton Bay loose its seasonality and become similar to the Gulf of Carpentaria  ?
\end{itemize}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Results}

\begin{itemize}
  \item 70\% of recruitment variability is explained by average maximum temperature in January at Cape Moreton lighthouse and SSB
  \item the interaction term is not significant
  \item a parabolic effect of temperature [ biologically more realistic ] provides as good a fit as the linear
  \item Recruitment increased x folds for each degree of temperature over the past 20 years
\end{itemize}

