\newpage
\section{Detailed content of the article}


\noindent{\bf 1. Introduction}
\begin{itemize}

\item Temperature defines the geographic distribution of many species, in particular poikilothermes which body temperature is set by their environment. 

\item Tiger prawn ({\it Penaeus esculentus}) is a tropical crustacean endemic to Australia and found around the Northern half of this continent (map). Cool water ( $<$ 20 $^{o}$C) is probably the major physical factor limiting the distribution of juvenile P. esculentus in natural fisheries \citep{Keys2003325}. This species has been commercially fished in Moreton Bay at least since ..... At present, Moreton Bay is the southernmost commercial fishery for tiger prawn on the east coast of Australia. %although there has been anecdotal evidences of commercial catches of tiger prawn in the Clarence river. Moreton Bay is located at the southern limit of distribution. 

\item Adult {\it P. esculentus} are not efficient osmoregulators at salinities below 30 and 50\permil, their lower lethal limit is 10\permil  (Dall, 1981) [taken from \cite{Keys2003325}].

\item Nutrients limit primary production in tropical and substropical seas [ Ecology by C. Krebs ]. Primary productivity can be predicted from a knowledge of light and biomass of chlorophyll and the action of limiting nutrients is on the biomass of chlorophyll in the phytoplankton.

%\item Global warming is impacting marine ecosystems. Changes in marine population distributions have been observed with polewards and deeper movements being documented. 

\item The distribution and abundance of many fishes and invertebrates have shifted poleward and/or to deeper, cooler waters (IPCC, high confidence). Many marine species changed their distribution in response to rise sea temperatures (CITE). Climate change will almost certainly shift the distribution of tiger prawn southwards placing Moreton Bay closer to the center of its distribution.

\item In response to further warming by 1Â°C or more by the mid 21st century and beyond, ocean-wide changes in ecosystem properties are projected to continue (high confidence). Large irreversible shifts in the spatial distribution of species and seasonal timing of their activities (feeding, growth, development, behaviors, and productivity) will have implications for species composition, and ecosystem goods and services. [IPCC 6.3.1, 6.4, 6.5, 6.6]

\item By the mid 21st century, the spatial shifts of marine species will cause species richness to increase at mid and high latitudes (high confidence) and to decrease at tropical latitudes (medium confidence), resulting in global redistribution of catch potential for fishes and invertebrates, with implications for food security (medium confidence)
% of many species and their responses to climate change. Shifting temperature means and extremes alter 
%habitat (e.g., sea ice and coastal), and cause changes in abundance through local extinctions and latitudinal 
%expansions or shifts (very high confidence)

\item What was the impetus to develop this analysis ? What approach did we used ? What were the specific difficulty of the analysis ? How did we approach the problem ? 

\item Brown tiger prawn displays a range of strategies to minimize the risk of predation. Prawns buries in the substrate during the day and emerge shortly after dusk to feed until towards the end of the night \citep{hill87a}, constraining trawlers to operate at night when tiger prawn catch rates are higher \citep{garcia1981life}. Temperature is known to determine the duration of emergence \citep{hil85a} by regulating the digestion speed and increasing the frequency an animal has to feed each night.

\item {\bf What did we know ?}\cite{hil85a} described experimentally a positive relationship between temperature and emergence time (Fig.~\ref{fig:EstimatesOfAvailability}). \cite{2013arXiv1306.3619K} identified that it could explain the variation of catchability in the tiger prawn fishery in Moreton Bay using average monthly temperature records. The present work extend this approach by combining daily estimate of temperature into the model of the dynamics of the fishery to assess (a) if it improves the fit of the model to the data and (b) allow to evidence effect such as the variability of timing in recruitment happening a the time-scale of weeks rather than months.

\item Describe the study area

\end{itemize}

\noindent {\bf 2. Materials and methods}\\

\noindent {\it 2.1 Climate data}
\begin{itemize}
\item BOM stations around Moreton Bay
\item Temperature data
\item Rainfall data
\end{itemize}

\noindent {\it 2.2 Recruitment and spawning stock biomass estimates}
\begin{itemize}
\item Delay difference model
\item Recruitment estimates
\item Spawning stock biomass estimates
\end{itemize}

\noindent {\it 2.3 Stock recruitment relationship}
\begin{itemize}
\item Ricker model and linearisation
\item Multiple linear regression, stepwise selection of environmental variables
\item Steepness of Ricker relation and $\frac{dR}{dS}$
\end{itemize}


\noindent {\bf 3. Results}\\
\noindent {\it 3.1 Recent trends in temperature}
\begin{itemize}
\item temperature trends from 1960 to 2015 [ highlight 1990 to 2010 ]
\item Is there evidence of a warming in the temperature time serie ?
\end{itemize}

\noindent {\it 3.2 Variable explaining recruitment variability}
\begin{itemize}
\item Effects of temperature and SSB
\item Compare a model with SSB, temp + SSB and temp * SSB -> no effect of interaction
\item Compare a model with a parabolic function of temperature
\end{itemize}

\noindent {\it 3.3 Effect of temperature on productivity}
\begin{itemize}
\item The steepness of Ricker' SRR is related to temperature
\item Steepness as a linear function of temperature
\item Steepness as a non-linear function of temperature
\end{itemize}

\noindent {\bf 4. Discussion}\\

\begin{itemize}
\item This work suggested that increased tiger prawn production observed between 1990 and 2010 was to a large extent driven by environmental changes that benefited this species in Moreton Bay. And to a lower extent by the reduction in fishing pressure induced by economic factors. Both factors worked synergestically to produce a more productive stock at the end of the period. The synchrony of these 2 factors which shifted around 2000 is fortuitious.
\item These results imply that further global warming will increase even more the productivity of brown tiger prawn in Moreton Bay
\item Aquaculture research suggest that the optimal water temperature is between 30 and 35 $^{o}$C
\item How do you deal with confounding between increasing fishing power and rising sea temperature ? is there confounding ? On reflection, it is quite obvious why statistics on observational data cannot tease apart the interacting effects: the confounding takes place because poor recruitments lead to poor spawning stocks (as well as vice-versa) \citep{Wal&Mar2004b}, p.175.
\item Is increase of recruitment due to increase in fecundity, longer spawning/reproduction period, higher survival rates from eggs to recruitment ?
\item This work suggest that from a situation of un-predictability, we are now in a position to predict good/bad years using average temperature in January at Cape Moreton lighthouse station and SSB.
\end{itemize}


