\section{Citations}

\begin{itemize}
\item "There is one generalization that stands out: correlations for populations at the limit of a species' geographical range have often remained statistically signficant when re-examined." \citep{Myers:1998}
\item "Environment-recruitment correlations for populations at the geographical limit of a species range were often confirmed if the sign of the predicted correlation was appropriate" \citep{Myers:1998}
\item Re-iterate that max. air temperature are strongly correlated with water temperature (cite the most recent paper), hence water temperature have risen inline with max air temperature increasing tiger prawn productivity in Moreton Bay.
\item When the mean recruitment relationship appears to be changing in a persistent way (with nonstationarity or long-period regime shifts represented by a very high autocorrelation in the recruitment anomalies), the best policy may still be a fixed-escapement or fixed-exploitation rate rule, but with the parameters of the rule adjusted each year by essentially assuming that the most recent anomalies will persist into the future. Persistent changes in recruitment relationships appear to be common today \citep{Wal&Mar2004b}.
\item Climate change will affect the benchmarks used in fisheries management. Understanding and quantifying the effect of climate change on populations in combination with the effect of exploitation is a major challenge to rebuilding and maintaining sustainable fisheries in the coming decades \citep{Hare2010a}.
\item Including temperature in the stock-recruitment relationship permitted the detection of a significant compensatory population effect (e.g., a dome-shaped stock-recruitment function) that was masked by temperature-driven variability  \citep{Hare2010a}.
\item In any region, some species will be positively affected by climate change while others will be negatively affected \citep{Hare2010a}.
\item Because black tiger prawns are a tropical species, their best growth rates occur when water temperatures are 25-30oC. Feeding stops at around 20$^{o}$C and death will occur around 14-15$^{o}$C. This temperature range limits production to one crop during summer in areas south of Mackay and two crops between Cardwell and Cooktown, provided good management, controlled stocking rates and selective harvesting are in place. (copied from \url{https://www.business.qld.gov.au/industry/fisheries/aquaculture/aquaculture-species/black-tiger-prawn-aquaculture/cultural-environment-tiger-prawns})
\item Growth of penaeid prawns in ponds is usually much faster than in the wild. Tiger prawns can be grown from postlarvae to a market size of 30g or more in 3-6 months, depending upon conditions in the pond, especially temperature and stocking density. The optimum temperature ranges for growth of tiger prawns and school prawns are 25-35$^{o}$C and 21-27$^{o}$C respectively. Outside these ranges growth rates are slowed down. (copied from \url{http://www.dpi.nsw.gov.au/fisheries/aquaculture/publications/species-saltwater/prawns})
\item \cite{Chaitanawisuti2013a} showed that temperature had a greater influence on survival of postlarvae P. monodon than salinity and low water temperature (29$^{o}$C) gave better larval survival than higher water temperatures (33$^{o}$C and 35$^{o}$C)
\item In their native range, tiger shrimp mature and breed in tropical marine habitats. Larvae, juveniles and sub-adults occupy shallow coastal estuaries, lagoons, and mangrove areas. Sub-adults subsequently move offshore, where they mature and breed, living on sand or muddy-sand bottom in up to 110 m water depth (Holthuis 1980). Temperature is an important environmental variable that influences not only the success of P. monodon culture, but also the survival and dispersal of wild P. monodon in areas where it is introduced. Survival and growth are optimal at temperatures between 28$^{o}$C and 33$^{o}$C, but growth is unlikely below 20$^{o}$C (Lumare et al. 1993). 
\item Environmental requirement for tiger prawn habitat, p.179 in \cite{das2014estuarine}: salinity ranges between 10 and 25 ppt; optimal temperature range for good growth and survival rates of tiger prawn ({\it penaeus monodon} ?) is 25--30$^{o}$C; minimum acceptable dissolve oxygen (DO) level is 3--4 mg/L; water PH of 5 and below is lethal to prawns like tiger prawns. pH range between 7.0--8.5 is optimal for growth and development of prawn; Presence of hydrogen sulphide (H2S) and low DO levels are detrimental to their survival as tiger prawns are bottom dweller.
\item  Fastest growth of juvenile tiger prawns ({\it Penaeus esculentus}) was estimated to be at 30 $^{o}$C and 30 per thousands \citep{O'Brien1994133}
\item "... the walleyed pollock population of the Bering Sea and Gulf of Alaska is presently the largest fished stock in the world. ... However, the recent years have lacked sustained periods of good recruitment, apparently because of climate-related changes in ocean processes \citep{bakun1996patterns}.
\item Rivers generally contain nutrient levels that range from a few times to several orders of magnitude higher than the nutrient level of surface coastal water. Accordingly, estuaries and the ocean areas off mouths of rivers tend to be particularly productive segments of the marine habitat \citep{bakun1996patterns}.
\end{itemize}

